69491\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"\">\n        <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2014/06/26/140627TGFSChefNEW-16x9.mp4\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2014/06/26/140627TGFSChefNEW.webm\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2014/06/26/140627TGFSChefNEW_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"></source><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2014/06/26/140627TGFSChefNEW_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"></source>\n      </video><p>Having become the most unlikely blockbuster director on the block, <em>Iron Man's</em> Jon Favreau goes back to his swinging indie roots – albeit with a VIP guest list. Working from his own script, he plays frustrated chef Carl Casper, forced by his restaurateur boss (Dustin Hoffman) to repeat the same old dishes until a snippy review provokes a meltdown that goes viral. Out of a job, and out of sorts with his habitually disappointed son (Emjay Anthony), Carl decides to reinvent himself with the aid of a Twitter account and a taco food truck. For all its reheated film-food cliches (cooking as a metaphor for bonding – sexual, fraternal, familial) and refried road-movie beans, <em>Chef</em> slips a few tasty side dishes around its meat-and-potatoes main course. John Leguizamo's sous-chef sauciness lends spice to Favreau's honest Joe schtick, while Robert Downey Jr makes a meal of an <em>amuse-bouche</em> cameo as Carl's ex-wife's ex-husband. Meanwhile, Scarlett Johansson and Sofia Vergara are on hand to prove that, in Hollywood, sexy heft remains an essentially male prerogative. At times it resembles a glorified advert for Twitter, but compared to Google-backed abomination <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/movie/155768/internship\" title=\"\"><em>The Internship</em></a> with which Favreau's former partner-in-crime <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jan/09/vince-vaughn-delivery-man-will-ferrell-bill-murray\" title=\"\">Vince Vaughn</a> sold what's left of his soul, such product placement appears innocuous indeed.</p>","headline":"Chef review – Jon Favreau cooks up a tasty food movie","trailText":"<p>The indie film-maker goes back to his roots with this tale of a chef who rediscovers his love for cooking, writes <strong>Mark Kermode</strong></p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/6/26/1403789199298/Jon-Favreau-centre-in-Che-006.jpg","wordcount":"208","commentable":"true","starRating":"3","byline":"Mark Kermode, Observer film critic","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-07-26T13:23:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jun/29/chef-review-jon-favreau-tasty-food-movie","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/2014/jun/29/chef-review-jon-favreau-tasty-food-movie","tags":[{"id":"film/chef","webTitle":"Chef","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/chef","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/chef","references":[]},{"id":"film/drama","webTitle":"Drama","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/drama","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/film/drama","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/new-review/critics","webTitle":"Critics","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/new-review/critics","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/new-review/critics","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/new-review","webTitle":"The New Review","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/new-review","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/new-review","references":[]},{"id":"film/comedy","webTitle":"Comedy","type":"keyword","sectionId":"film","sectionName":"Film","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/film/comedy","apiUrl":"http://b